<subSubSection pageId="501" pageNumber="502" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="501" pageNumber="502">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirby" authorityYear="1837" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Stereocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="501" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Stereocerus</taxonomicName>
Kirby, 1837: 34. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirby" authorityYear="1837" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Stereocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="501" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="501" pageNumber="502">Stereocerus similis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Kirby, 1837 (= 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dejean" baseAuthorityYear="1831" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Feronia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="501" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haematopus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="501" pageNumber="502">Feronia haematopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dejean, 1831) by monotypy. Etymology. From the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="501" pageNumber="502">stereos</emphasis>
(solid, firm, hard) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="501" pageNumber="502">ceros</emphasis>
(horn, by extension antenna), alluding to the stout antennae (&quot;antennae robust&quot;) of the adults [masculine].
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="501" pageNumber="502">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tschitscherine" authorityYear="1896" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Boreobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="501" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Boreobia</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Tschitschérine">Tschitscherine</normalizedToken>
, 1896b: 375. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tschitscherine" authorityYear="1896" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Feronia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="501" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imitatrix">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="501" pageNumber="502">Feronia imitatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Tschitschérine">Tschitscherine</normalizedToken>
, 1896 (= 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dejean" baseAuthorityYear="1831" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Feronia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="501" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haematopus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="501" pageNumber="502">Feronia haematopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dejean, 1831) designated by Bousquet (1984a: 4). Etymology. From the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="501" pageNumber="502">boreas</emphasis>
(north) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="501" pageNumber="502">bios</emphasis>
(life) [feminine].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="501" pageNumber="502" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="501" pageNumber="502">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="501" pageNumber="502">Two Holarctic species in the arctic, subarctic, and boreal regions.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
